[{"id"  :"ltr_rel7020","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-07-24","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7020.txt","description"  :"I cannot express the joy I feel, at the beautiful victory of the 21st.","source"  :"50","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Pierre Gustave Toutant","r_lastName"  :"Beauregard","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7050","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1862-06-11","city"  :"Near Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7050.txt","description"  :"Your recent successes have been the cause of the liveliest joy in this army as well as in the country.","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Thomas","r_lastName"  :"Jackson","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7051","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1862-06-29","city"  :"Headquarters Department Of Northern Virginia","state"  :"","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7051.txt","description"  :"I regret much that you have made so little progress to-day in pursuit of the enemy. In order to reap the fruits of our victory the pursuit should be most vigorous.","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"J","r_lastName"  :"Macgruder","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7052","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1862-09-02","city"  :"","state"  :"","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7052.txt","description"  :"The body of General Philip Kearny was brought from the field last night","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"John","r_lastName"  :"Pope","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7053","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1862-09-08","city"  :"Headquarters Near Fredericktown","state"  :"MD","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7053.txt","description"  :"The present position of affairs, in my opinion, places it in the power of the government of the Confederate States to propose with propriety to that of the United States the recognition of our independence.","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Jefferson","r_lastName"  :"Davis","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7054","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1862-09-08","city"  :"Fredericktown","state"  :"MD","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7054.txt","description"  :"It is right that you should know the purpose that brought the army under my command within the limits of your State, so far as that purpose concerns yourselves.","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"","r_lastName"  :"","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"group"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7055","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-03-02","city"  :"Headquarters Confederate States Armies","state"  :"","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7055.txt","description"  :"Sincerely desiring to leave nothing untried which may put an end to the calamities of war, I propose to meet you at such convenient time and place as you may designate","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Ulysses","r_lastName"  :"Grant","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7056","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-04-08","city"  :"","state"  :"","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7056.txt","description"  :"I received at a late hour your note of to-day. In mine of yesterday I did not intend to propose the surrender of the Army of Northern Virginia, but to ask the terms of your proposition.","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Ulysses","r_lastName"  :"Grant","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7057","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1864-08-26","city"  :"","state"  :"","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7057.txt","description"  :"I take great pleasure in presenting to you my congratulations upon the conduct of the men of your corps.","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"E","r_lastName"  :"Anderson","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7058","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1864-08-29","city"  :"Camp Petersburg","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7058.txt","description"  :"You will soon be as well as ever, and we shall all be rejoiced at your return. You must not, however, become impatient at the gradual progress you must necessarily make","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"James","r_lastName"  :"Longstreet","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7059","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-02-22","city"  :"Headquarters Confederate States Armies","state"  :"","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7059.txt","description"  :"I agree with you entirely in believing that if we had gold we could get sufficient supplies for our army, but the great difficulty is to obtain the gold.","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"James","r_lastName"  :"Longstreet","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7060","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-02-25","city"  :"Headquarters","state"  :"","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7060.txt","description"  :"I fear I did not entirely comprehend your views expressed in your letter of the 14th. I think, however, my reply meets your supposition, in the event of concentration by the enemy.","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"James","r_lastName"  :"Longstreet","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7061","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-03-02","city"  :"Headquarters","state"  :"","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7061.txt","description"  :"I have received to-day your letter of the 1st instant, and concluded to propose an interview to General Grant.","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"James","r_lastName"  :"Longstreet","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7062","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1866-01-19","city"  :"Lexington","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7062.txt","description"  :"I have almost forgotten what it contained, but I hope it will inform you of my purpose in writing a history of the campaigns in Virginia, and of the object that I have in view, so that you may give me all the information in your power.","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"James","r_lastName"  :"Longstreet","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7063","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1866-01-26","city"  :"Lexington","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7063.txt","description"  :"I am much obliged to you for your business card, and the pleasure it has afforded me to know that you have entered into partnership.","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"James","r_lastName"  :"Longstreet","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7064","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1866-03-09","city"  :"Lexington","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7064.txt","description"  :"Can you not occupy your leisure time in preparing your memoirs of the war Every officer whose position and character would give weight to his statements ought to do so. It is the only way in which we may hope that fragments of truth will reach poster","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"James","r_lastName"  :"Longstreet","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7065","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1866-05-25","city"  :"Lexington","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7065.txt","description"  :"I am much pleased to know that your prospects in a commercial point of view are good and progressive. I hope they may regularly and surely advance.","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"James","r_lastName"  :"Longstreet","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7066","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-04-07","city"  :"","state"  :"","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7066.txt","description"  :"I reciprocate your desire to avoid useless effusion of blood","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Ulysses","r_lastName"  :"Grant","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7067","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-03-02","city"  :"Headquarters Confederate States Armies","state"  :"","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7067.txt","description"  :"...expressed some apprehension lest the general terms used by you with reference to the exchange of political prisoners should be construed to include those charged with capital offences.","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Ulysses","r_lastName"  :"Grant","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7068","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1863-08-31","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7068.txt","description"  :"I have wished for several days past to return to the army, but have been detained by the President.","source"  :"94","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"James","r_lastName"  :"Longstreet","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7450","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-11-24","city"  :"Coosawhatchie","state"  :"SC","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7450.txt","description"  :"I recollect, however, that at the interview at which I was present Mr. Chesnut urged, on the part of General Beauregard, the importance of reinforcing the army of the Potomac to enable it to oppose the Federal forces","source"  :"96","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Jefferson","r_lastName"  :"Davis","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel7451","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1863-08-08","city"  :"Camp Orange","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel7451.txt","description"  :"The general remedy for the want of success in a military commander is his removal. This is natural, and in many instances proper.","source"  :"96","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Jefferson","r_lastName"  :"Davis","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel491","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1848-06-30","city"  :"arlington","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel491.txt","description"  :"robert lee writes his brother of his homecoming after the mexican war. also note by the biographer christopher lee","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"robert","lastName"  :"lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"s","r_lastName"  :"lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel492","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1853-02-25","city"  :"west point","state"  :"NY","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel492.txt","description"  :"robert lee writes his daughter annie from west point, Feb 25th 1853","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"robert","lastName"  :"lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"annie","r_lastName"  :"lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel493","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1859-12-01","city"  :"harper's ferry","state"  :"WV","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel493.txt","description"  :"robert lee writes his wife mary about john brown from harper's ferry, dec 10th 1859","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"robert","lastName"  :"lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"mary","r_lastName"  :"lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel494","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-04-20","city"  :"arlington","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel494.txt","description"  :"robert lee writes his resignation letter to general winfield scott","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"robert","lastName"  :"lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"winfield","r_lastName"  :"scott","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel495","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-04-20","city"  :"Arlington","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel495.txt","description"  :"Robert E. Lee letter to sister Anne Marshall, April 20, 1861","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Anne","r_lastName"  :"Marshall","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel496","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-04-20","city"  :"Arlington","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel496.txt","description"  :"Robert E. Lee letter to brother, Captain Sydney Smith Lee, of the United States Navy, April 20, 1861","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Sydney","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel497","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1868-02-25","city"  :"Lexington","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel497.txt","description"  :"Robert E. Lee letter - account of his resignation from the United States Army","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Reverdy","r_lastName"  :"Johnson","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel498","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-04-26","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel498.txt","description"  :"I am very anxious about you","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel499","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-05-02","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel499.txt","description"  :"regretful explaination that she can not join him","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel500","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-05-08","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel500.txt","description"  :"I grieve at the necessity that drives you from your home","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel501","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-05-11","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel501.txt","description"  :"retire further from the scene of war","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel502","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-05-16","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel502.txt","description"  :" telling of the Episcopal Convention of the Diocese of Virginia","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel503","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-05-25","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel503.txt","description"  :"I sympathise deeply in your feelings at leaving your dear home","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel504","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-05-28","city"  :"Manassas","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel504.txt","description"  :"I am very much occupied in examining matters","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel505","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-06-09","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel505.txt","description"  :"I have just returned from a visit to the batteries and troops...","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel506","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-07-12","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel506.txt","description"  :"I am very anxious to get into the field","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel507","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-07-21","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel507.txt","description"  :"That indeed was a glorious victory","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel508","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-08-04","city"  :"Huntersville","state"  :"WV","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel508.txt","description"  :"I reached here yesterday...","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel509","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-08-09","city"  :"Camp at Valley Mountain","state"  :"WV","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel509.txt","description"  :"The mountains are beautiful","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel510","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-08-29","city"  :"Valley Mountain","state"  :"WV","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel510.txt","description"  :"It rains here all the time, literally","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"","r_lastName"  :"","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel511","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-09-01","city"  :"Valley Mountain","state"  :"WV","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel511.txt","description"  :"I am very glad you are enabled to see so many of your friends","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel512","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-09-09","city"  :"Valley Mountain","state"  :"WV","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel512.txt","description"  :"I hope from the tone of your letter that you feel better","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel513","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-09-17","city"  :"Valley Mountain","state"  :"WV","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel513.txt","description"  :"I can not tell you my regret and mortification at the untoward events that caused the failure of the plan","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel514","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-09-17","city"  :"Valley Mountain","state"  :"WV","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel514.txt","description"  :"Robert E. Lee letter to Governor John Letcher, September 17, 1861","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"John","r_lastName"  :"Letcher","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel515","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-09-26","city"  :"Camp on Sewell's Mountain","state"  :"WV","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel515.txt","description"  :"I have no doubt the yarn ones you mention will be very acceptable to the men here or elsewhere","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel516","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-10-07","city"  :"sewell's mountain","state"  :"WV","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel516.txt","description"  :"at the time of their reception the enemy was threatening an attack.","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"robert","lastName"  :"lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"mary","r_lastName"  :"lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel518","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-11-05","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel518.txt","description"  :"Saturday evening I tried to get down to you","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel526","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1862-01-28","city"  :"Coosawhatchie","state"  :"SC","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel526.txt","description"  :"I was called to Charleston by the appearance off the bar of a fleet of vessels","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel527","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1862-02-08","city"  :"Savannah","state"  :"GA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel527.txt","description"  :"I have been here ever since, endeavouring to push forward the work for the defense of the city","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel528","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1862-02-23","city"  :"Savannah","state"  :"GA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel528.txt","description"  :"I am engaged in constructing a line of defense at Fort Jackson","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel529","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1862-03-02","city"  :"Savannah","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel529.txt","description"  :"Our people have not been earnest enough, have thought too much of themselves and their ease","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Annie","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel530","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1862-03-14","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel530.txt","description"  :"I have been placed on duty here to conduct operations under the direction of the President","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel531","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1862-03-15","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel531.txt","description"  :"I hope our son will do his duty and make a good soldier","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel519","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-11-18","city"  :"Savannah","state"  :"GA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel519.txt","description"  :"You probably have seen the operations of the enemy's fleet","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel520","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-11-15","city"  :"Charleston","state"  :"SC","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel520.txt","description"  :"your letters always give me great pleasure","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mildred","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel521","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-11-22","city"  :"Savannah","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel521.txt","description"  :"The horse-chestnut you mention in the garden was planted by my mother","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel522","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-12-08","city"  :"Coosawhatchie","state"  :"SC","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel522.txt","description"  :"One of the miseries of war is that there is no Sabbath, and the current of work and strife has no cessation","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Annie","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel523","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-12-02","city"  :"Coosawhatchie","state"  :"SC","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel523.txt","description"  :"am delighted to learn that you are all well and so many of you are together","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel524","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1861-12-25","city"  :"Coosawhatchie","state"  :"SC","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel524.txt","description"  :" on Christmas Day. 1861","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel525","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1862-01-18","city"  :"Coosawhatchie","state"  :"SC","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel525.txt","description"  :"I had the gratification at length of visiting my father's grave","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel533","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1862-04-29","city"  :"richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel533.txt","description"  :"general robert e lee letter to general T.J Jackson April, 29th 1862","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"robert","lastName"  :"lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"thomas","r_lastName"  :"jackson","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel534","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1862-12-26","city"  :"camp fredericksburg","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel534.txt","description"  :"robert lee writes his daughter agnes from camp fredericksburg, dec 26, 1862","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"robert","lastName"  :"lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"agnes","r_lastName"  :"lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel535","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1863-02-06","city"  :"camp fredericksburg","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel535.txt","description"  :"...the roads are wretched, almost impassable","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"robert","lastName"  :"lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"agnes","r_lastName"  :"lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel536","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1863-02-23","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel536.txt","description"  :"The weather is now very hard upon our poor bushmen.","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel537","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1863-08-13","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel537.txt","description"  :"...a day of fasting, humiliation, and prayer.","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"","r_lastName"  :"","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel538","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1863-11-01","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel538.txt","description"  :"I am sorry you find such difficulty in procuring yarn for socks, etc.","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel539","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1863-11-05","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel539.txt","description"  :"I had not been on horseback for five days previously and feared I should not get through.","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel540","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1864-04-12","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel540.txt","description"  :"...My anxiety on the subject of provisions for the army is so great that I cannot refrain from expressing it","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Jefferson","r_lastName"  :"Davis","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel541","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1864-11-06","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel541.txt","description"  :"Robert E. Lee letter to his youngest daughter Mildred ...Now in your youth you must be careful to discipline your thoughts, words, and actions","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mildred","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel542","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-08-26","city"  :"Near Cartersville","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel542.txt","description"  :"Robert E. Lee letter to prospective publisher.","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Joseph","r_lastName"  :"Topham","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel543","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-04-10","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel543.txt","description"  :"Robert E. Lee letter to confederate soldiers ...the Army of Northern Virginia has been compelled to yield to overwhelming numbers and resources","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"","r_lastName"  :"","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel544","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-06-21","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel544.txt","description"  :"...I propose establishing my family next week in Cumberland County, Virginia","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Albert","r_lastName"  :"Ordway","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel545","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-06-24","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel545.txt","description"  :"...I have just returned from a visit to your Uncle Carter","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Robert","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel546","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-08-21","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel546.txt","description"  :"...You must keep your eyes open, you precious boy, and not run against noxious vines and fevers","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Robert","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel547","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-07-29","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel547.txt","description"  :"...I want to get in some grass country, where the natural product of the land will do much for my subsistence","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"William Fitzhugh","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel548","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-08-24","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel548.txt","description"  :"...The proper education of youth requires not only great ability,but I fear more strength than I now possess","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"","r_lastName"  :"","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel549","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-09-19","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel549.txt","description"  :"on riding up to the hotel was met by Professor White, of Washington College","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel550","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-10-29","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel550.txt","description"  :"...You know I am a poor hand and can do nothing without your advice","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mildred","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel551","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-10-06","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel551.txt","description"  :"...Though marble to women, he is so only externally, and you will find him warm and cheering","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Agnes","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel552","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-11-16","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel552.txt","description"  :"...As she would not marry Custis, she may marry whom she chooses.","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Agnes","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel553","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-11-21","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel553.txt","description"  :"received your letter of the 17th, and return the photographs with my signatures","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel554","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-11-20","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel554.txt","description"  :"I am much disappointed that you did not arrive on the boat last night","source"  :"20","firstName"  :"Robert","lastName"  :"Lee","pedigree"  :"null","r_firstName"  :"Mary","r_lastName"  :"Lee","r_pedigree"  :"null","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_rel555","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1865-12-05","city"  :"Richmond","state"  :"VA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_rel555.txt","description"  :"...I have autographed the photographs and send a gross of the latter and a lock of hair","source"  :"20","